[2026-03-18T12:00:20.671Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01AkcEb7YxjskjGM3vMZwEYz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MQwuEz5dZzzmtrFoQnHU1W","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"scan_id\": \"cdae3cf9-bf4c-4a49-8af0-9f557cbf7b25\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"scan_type\": \"tech_innovator\",\n    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    \"title\": \"Execution-aware work stealing with persona affinity\",\n    \"description\": \"getIdleWorker() (workerPool.ts:327-329) returns the first idle worker from a Set iterator — zero intelligence. Workers advertise capabilities (claude-cli version, image digest, network-policy support) and the orchestrator stores this in WorkerInfo, but the dispatcher ignores ALL of it. Meanwhile, dispatchToWorker (dispatcher.ts:387) resolves inference profiles, network policies, and credential sets per-persona — information that should inform WHICH worker receives the assignment. Build a scoring-based work-stealing scheduler: workers pull from a shared queue weighted by capability match (CLI version compatibility, digest verification), persona affinity (same worker for repeated executions of the same persona = warm sandbox/credential caches), and load balancing. PoC: implement a WorkerScorer that ranks idle workers by capability overlap + execution history, compare assignment quality vs random selection on a 4-worker cluster. Risk: scoring latency could slow dispatch under burst load; affinity logic must not starve workers that never had a given persona; work-stealing coordination complexity if workers can pull independently.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"This is not generic load balancing — it is domain-specific because persona executions have heterogeneous requirements (inference profiles requiring specific auth tokens, network policies requiring proxy-capable workers, Claude CLI version constraints). The current blind dispatch means an execution requiring network-policy enforcement might land on a worker without proxy support, or a persona with a specific inference profile might get assigned to a worker running an incompatible Claude CLI version. Affinity compounds: a worker that repeatedly runs the same persona can skip redundant sandbox setup and credential injection, reducing dispatch-to-first-output latency. This creates operational expertise in the system that competitors starting fresh cannot shortcut.\",\n    \"effort\": 8,\n    \"impact\": 9,\n    \"risk\": 7\n  }'","description":"Post idea 4: capability-aware routing"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1221,"cache_read_input_tokens":63946,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1221},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a98dd510-3145-4e13-a658-c8990d01d642","uuid":"e23c5103-d68e-4442-b7da-0af864781226"}
